It is rare that a stock becomes as hot as Tesla in 2020, I think Volkswagen in 2008 is the last time I remember anything like it. Therefore, putting a value on volatility is incredibly more difficult as markets diverge from normal "random walk"/Brownian motion - like behavior and become unstable. Didier Sornette in his brilliant but arguably out of left field book "Why Stock Markets Crash" compared the behavior in these scenarios to balancing a pen on your finger: it is not a matter of if, but when, the pen drops. The binomial path every trading session is not between up/down a certain multiple of sigma, but an increasingly large gain with high probability, versus total collapse.

Similiar to my colleagues, I note that there are several ways to tackle this problem - for example, we can use historical price data to forecast the price path of TSLA, or we can use options delta as a measure of finishing ITM for certain strikes. While using historical data to forecast future prices can lead to a variety of creative input in terms of how we want to model our data - I believe that the option's delta suffices as a measure that encapsulates a wide variety of modelling techniques. Further, one major factor that would've impacted TSLA's price was the inclusion in the S&P 500 index, however, we now know that TSLA was not included in the latest re balancing for the S&P.

There are two obvious ways of estimating this, (1) a random walk, (2) by looking at option prices. I first implemented the random walk. The two main problems here are estimating the future daily returns and the volatility that TSLA will realize between now and Sep 22. For returns, I simply chose to use the S&P500 over the last 5 years. This assumes that TSLA will have market returns which I am not sure is accurate given how it has moved over the past few months but I dont think I am better able to predict this value myself. For volatility I looked at 30-50 day realized volon bloomberg which is ~80. I added 10% to this due to the potential vol event regarding the S&P 500 add.

Baseline: Predicting Tesla stock price is very difficult given that due to immense retail flow it has been trading at multiples and valuations that are very hard to justify using fundamental analysis. However, this has been the case for years now, therefore we need to find other ways to put a probability distribution around the stock price. A common way to do it is to use implied option prices and the values that market implies. Option deltas can often be used as an approximate for the probability that the markets imply for the event to occur. We use these values to come up with a probability distribution for the price. There are two main reason why such method could be used and might prove valid: (1) the wisdom of the crowd cannot be underestimated and has proven to be often right, (2) given how detached Tesla is from its fundamental valuation, it is the market that is driving and deciding about the price and not the other way round.

Question: Base rate: I simulated the price of Tesla at time t as a Geometric Brownian motion. For mu the percentage drift and sigma the percentage volatility I used historical returns of the stocks on different horizons: from July 1st, Jan 1st 20 or Jan1st 19. For each case, I have then run 100000 Monte Carlo simulations to get some probabilities for each range. For Jan1st 20 (jan 1st 19) got the following proba: Less than $400.00 31% (30), Between $400.00 and $450.00, inclusive 17% (24), More than $450.00 but less than $500.00 18% (20), Between $500.00 and $550.00 12% (13), More than $550.00 22% (13).

I used TSLA options data to back out the delta, which is the risk neutral probability under current implied volatility levels that the option will end up in the money. This is a rough heuristic after all (see risk neutral vs. real world probability difference here: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_finance) and the delta is best for approximation near the strike. However, since I have no strong prior on this and TSLA is very volatile stock (say 130 IV), I am basing my predictions on the market implied (risk-neutral) odds.

Took daily return since start of 2018, found the std and mean, and sampled 12 days from a normal dist with this std and mean to get my price estimate for sep 22. Repeated 100k times to inform probabilities of each bin. Also repeated for data just starting in 2019 and just the last 45 days of data. My guess is a weighted avg of these three, with more weight given to the run where I only used the last 45 days. Plus I'm a TSLA fan so then I needed to skew it by a couple percent -- Sept 22 is TSLA battery day so I would guess there will be a decent amount of retail enthusiasm during that trading day and the lead up. Also potential S&P inclusion makes me skew higher. In total I'll take about 10% from lower bins and add to higher ones
